onomic discrepancies remain across countries. Why are some societies but not others able to encourage investments in places, people, and productivity? The answer, the book argues, lies to a large extent in institutional differences across societies. Such institutions are wide-ranging and include formal constitutional arrangements, the role of economic and political elites, informal institutions that promote investment and knowledge transfer, and others. Two core themes run through the contributors’ essays. First, what constraints do institutions place on the power of the executive to prevent it from extorting the investments and effort of other people and institutions? Second, when are productive institutions self-enforcing? Institutions and Economic Performance is unique in its melding of economics, political science, history, and sociology to address its central question.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aEconomic development. 0aPolitical culture. 0aPublic administration. 0aRegional economic disparities. 0aSocial institutions. 0aSocial structure. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / International / General.2bisacsh1 aAcemoglu, Daron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAghion, Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlesina, Alberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBautista, María Angélica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBesley, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiermeier, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrelichman, Mauricio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFearon, James D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFong, Pohan, 